y [NASA](https://www.nasa.gov/), the search for extraterrestrial intelligence is an ongoing effort, with scientists using a variety of methods to detect signs of technology used by extraterrestrial civilizations. The detection of technosignatures is a challenging task, and the effects of stellar space weather can make it even more difficult. However, the study's findings also suggest that the effects of stellar space weather on radio signals can be mitigated by using more advanced detection methods. For example, [the Breakthrough Listen initiative](https://breakthroughinitiatives.org/initiative/1) is using machine learning algorithms to detect signs of technology used by extraterrestrial civilizations. The initiative is a 10-year survey of the Milky Way galaxy, using radio and optical telescopes to detect signs of technology used by extraterrestrial civilizations. The study's findings highlight the importance of considering the effects of stellar space weather on radio signals when searching for technosignatures. This requires a more nuanced approach to the search, taking into account the various factors that can affect the detection of radio signals. The [Astrophysical Journal](https://iopscience.iop.org/journal/0004-637X) has published numerous studies on the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, and this study is a significant contribution to the field. The search for technosignatures is an ongoing effort, and the study's findings suggest that the effects of stellar space weather on radio signals should be taken into account when searching for technosignatures. The study's findings also highlight the importance of continued research and development in the field of astrobiology and the search for extraterrestrial intelligence.0:{"buildId":"8BczN53qI8xXbjPXJW-p6","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 py-8","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-text-secondary hover:text-accent-cyan transition-colors mb-6","children":[["$","svg",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg","width":24,"height":24,"viewBox":"0 0 24 24","fill":"none","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":2,"strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","className":"lucide lucide-arrow-left w-4 h-4","aria-hidden":"true","children":[["$","path","1l729n",{"d":"m12 19-7-7 7-7"}],["$","path","x3x0zl",{"d":"M19 12H5"}],"$undefined"]}],"Back to Home"]}],["$","$L3",null,{"category":"space"}],["$","$L4",null,{"category":"space"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-8","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"category-badge category-badge-space mb-2 inline-block","children":"Space"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"font-heading text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-text-primary","children":["Space"," News"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary mt-2","children":[34," article","s"]}]]}],false,["$","$L5",null,{"articles":[{"id":"2026-03-23-nasas-ignition-plan-science-first-spectacle-second","dbId":640,"title":"NASA’s Ignition Plan: Science First, Spectacle Second","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When NASA unveiled its \"Ignition\" initiative this week, the video title could have promised another dazzling spaceflight spectacle.","execSummary":"NASA's 'Ignition' plan shifts focus from symbolic milestones to operational infrastructure—linking ISS longevity, lunar base development, and fission power into a cohesive timeline. The significance lies in its concrete mechanisms (2025–2026 targets) and the tension between scientific goals and strategic partnerships, where private-sector delays could derail progress.","keyPoints":["Ignition integrates space policy with science","Moon Base and ISS leaders at the table","Fission power moves from theory to mission"],"source":{"name":"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYH6W9iCs2E"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/nasas-ignition-plan-science-first-spectacle-second/main.jpg","alt":"NASA’s Ignition Plan: Science First, Spectacle Second"},"subtitle":"Tri programa, jedan cilj: od orbite do trajnih istraživačkih postaja","subtitleEn":"The agency’s new roadmap prioritizes measurable discovery over flash—here’s why that matters","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/nasas-ignition-plan-science-first-spectacle-second/subtitle.png","alt":"The agency’s new roadmap prioritizes measurable discovery over flash—here’s why that matters"},"tags":["NASA","Lunar Base","Space Exploration"],"geo":{"name":"Washington, D.C., USA","lat":38.9072,"lon":-77.0369,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$6","videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYH6W9iCs2E"},{"id":"2026-03-23-starships-sixth-flight-proves-reuse-is-the-real-ra","dbId":639,"title":"Starship’s sixth flight proves reuse is the real race","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When SpaceX’s Starship lifted off from Starbase on November 19, the real story wasn’t the fire and thunder—it was the quiet confirmation that the most complex part of rocket reuse is becoming routine.","execSummary":"SpaceX's sixth Starship test marks a shift from spectacle to operational validation, with the Super Heavy booster demonstrating critical reuse maneuvers. The real significance lies in economic implications: full system reuse could drop orbital launch costs by an order of magnitude, enabling Mars missions and commercial orbital infrastructure. Next steps focus on orbital refueling simulations in Q1 2025, moving from testing to operational reality.","keyPoints":["Super Heavy’s 33-engine boostback burn confirmed operational","Stage separation now a solved variable in reuse timeline","Full-system reusability edges closer to economic viability"],"source":{"name":"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CMGiNKcVSek"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/starships-sixth-flight-proves-reuse-is-the-real-ra/main.jpg","alt":"Starship’s sixth flight proves reuse is the real race"},"subtitle":"Ponovna uporaba nije samo cilj – to je uvjet za Mars i komercijalnu orbitu","subtitleEn":"The milestone that shifts Starship from spectacle to system","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/starships-sixth-flight-proves-reuse-is-the-real-ra/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The milestone that shifts Starship from spectacle to system"},"tags":["Starship","Reusability","Mars Mission","SpaceX"],"geo":{"name":"Starbase, Boca Chica, Texas, USA","lat":25.9972,"lon":-97.1561,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$7","videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CMGiNKcVSek"},{"id":"2026-03-23-extragalactic-archaeology-maps-spiral-galaxy-evolu","dbId":626,"title":"Extragalactic Archaeology Maps Spiral Galaxy Evolution","titleEn":"Extragalactic Archaeology Maps Spiral Galaxy Evolution","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Galactic archaeology has long allowed astronomers to reconstruct the Milky Way's past by analyzing the chemical compositions and motions of its stars.","execSummary":"This study shifts galactic archaeology from the Milky Way to external galaxies, using chemical fingerprints to reconstruct their evolution—proving direct historical analysis is possible beyond simulations. The real impact lies in validating (or challenging) galaxy formation theories with empirical timelines, not just visual data.","keyPoints":["First archaeology study beyond Milky Way","Harvard team analyzes external spiral galaxy","New field opens comparative galactic research"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/extragalactic-archaeology-maps-spiral-galaxy-evolu/main.jpg","alt":"Extragalactic Archaeology Maps Spiral Galaxy Evolution"},"subtitle":"Metoda koja mijenja način na koji razumijemo rast udaljenih galaktika","subtitleEn":"The methodology that extends stellar archaeology beyond our galaxy","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/extragalactic-archaeology-maps-spiral-galaxy-evolu/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The methodology that extends stellar archaeology beyond our galaxy"},"tags":["Galactic Archaeology","Spiral Galaxy Dynamics","Galaxy Evolution"],"geo":{"name":"San Francisco, US","lat":37.7749,"lon":-122.4194,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$8","part1En":"$9","part2En":"$a"},{"id":"2026-03-23-complete-genetic-alphabet-found-in-asteroid-ryugu-","dbId":620,"title":"Complete Genetic Alphabet Found in Asteroid Ryugu Samples","titleEn":"Complete Genetic Alphabet Found in Asteroid Ryugu Samples","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The discovery of all five fundamental nucleobases in samples from asteroid Ryugu quietly reshapes our understanding of life's potential origins.","execSummary":"The discovery of all five nucleobases in Ryugu’s samples shifts the debate from *whether* life’s building blocks exist in space to *how common* they are—and what that implies for abiogenesis. This article dissects the mission’s precision, the scientific weight of a complete nucleobase set, and why this demands a rethink of prebiotic chemistry’s universality.","keyPoints":["All five nucleobases detected in Ryugu samples","Building blocks of life may be widespread","Hayabusa2 mission yields unexpected completeness"],"source":{"name":"Phys.org Space","url":"https://phys.org/news/2026-03-fundamental-life-genetic-code-asteroid.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/complete-genetic-alphabet-found-in-asteroid-ryugu-/main.jpg","alt":"Complete Genetic Alphabet Found in Asteroid Ryugu Samples"},"subtitle":"Zašto je ovo više od samo kemije – a kamo sreće u potrazi za podrijetlom života","subtitleEn":"Why the completeness of this discovery matters","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/complete-genetic-alphabet-found-in-asteroid-ryugu-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why the completeness of this discovery matters"},"tags":["Asteroid Ryugu","Origin of Life","Astrobiology"],"geo":{"name":"Sagamihara, Kanagawa, Japan [JAXA Institute of Space and Astronautical Science (ISAS) - Hayabusa2 mission control]","lat":35.5976,"lon":139.3889,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$b","part1En":"$c","part2En":"$d"},{"id":"2026-03-23-orbitiny-a-linux-desktop-that-bends-the-rules-of-p","dbId":618,"title":"Orbitiny: A Linux desktop that bends the rules of portability","titleEn":"Orbitiny: A Linux desktop that bends the rules of portability","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The line between an operating system and an application has always been rigid—until now.","execSummary":"Orbitiny, a Linux desktop that runs like an app, offers portability and performance without installation. This could revolutionize space research computing by simplifying system deployment in resource-limited environments like spacecraft or research stations.","keyPoints":["Linux desktop runs as a self-contained app","No installation, no VM—just native-like performance","Why this matters for remote and constrained environments"],"source":{"name":"ZDNet","url":"https://www.zdnet.com/article/orbitiny-portable-modular-unique-linux-desktop/"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/orbitiny-a-linux-desktop-that-bends-the-rules-of-p/main.jpg","alt":"Orbitiny: A Linux desktop that bends the rules of portability"},"subtitle":"Zašto je ovo važno za budućnost istraživanja svemirskih operativnih sustava?","subtitleEn":"When the operating system becomes just another application, the rules of deployment change. Here’s what that means for field research and edge computing.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/orbitiny-a-linux-desktop-that-bends-the-rules-of-p/subtitle.jpg","alt":"When the operating system becomes just another application, the rules of deployment change. Here’s what that means for field research and edge computing."},"tags":["Orbitiny","Linux","Space Operating Systems"],"geo":{"name":"Houston, TX","lat":29.5502,"lon":-95.097,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$e","part1En":"$f","part2En":"$10"},{"id":"2026-03-23-how-eu-law-is-quietly-reshaping-gaming-hardware-de","dbId":616,"title":"How EU law is quietly reshaping gaming hardware design","titleEn":"How EU law is quietly reshaping gaming hardware design","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The European Union’s right-to-repair legislation has done something rare: it has compelled a hardware giant to rethink a flagship product’s fundamental architecture.","execSummary":"Nintendo’s Switch 2 redesign for EU markets—mandating user-replaceable batteries—isn’t just a gaming story but a test case for how regulation can enforce sustainability in closed-tech ecosystems. The move, driven by EU consumer law, challenges industry norms and could set a precedent for modular design in electronics, with broader implications for e-waste reduction and right-to-repair advocacy.","keyPoints":["EU consumer law forces Nintendo’s Switch 2 redesign","Battery replacement becomes a hardware rights issue","Global ripple effects from regional regulatory pressure"],"source":{"name":"Eurogamer","url":"https://www.eurogamer.net/thanks-to-eu-consumer-law-nintendo-is-updating-the-switch-2-design-to-enable-european-players-to-replace-the-battery"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/how-eu-law-is-quietly-reshaping-gaming-hardware-de/main.jpg","alt":"How EU law is quietly reshaping gaming hardware design"},"subtitle":"Kako regulativa oblikuje hardver — i zašto je to važno izvan igara","subtitleEn":"When a single legal clause alters the trajectory of a billion-dollar product line","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/how-eu-law-is-quietly-reshaping-gaming-hardware-de/subtitle.jpg","alt":"When a single legal clause alters the trajectory of a billion-dollar product line"},"tags":["European Union","Sustainable Electronics","Right to Repair"],"geo":{"name":"Kyoto, Japan","lat":35.0116,"lon":135.7681,"countryCode":"JP"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$11","part1En":"$12","part2En":"$13"},{"id":"2026-03-23-obesity-therapy-could-determine-mars-mission-viabi","dbId":202,"title":"Obesity Therapy Could Determine Mars Mission Viability","titleEn":"Obesity Therapy Could Determine Mars Mission Viability","category":"space","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When we talk about obesity in the context of long-term space missions, the problem stops being aesthetic or even purely medical — it becomes an operational risk.","execSummary":"A phase 2 trial combining semaglutide and bimagrumab shows unprecedented fat loss with muscle preservation, offering potential solutions for long-duration space missions where muscle atrophy is a critical risk. The findings bridge metabolic research and space medicine, but raise questions about long-term safety and ethical use beyond clinical needs.","keyPoints":["Combined therapy preserves muscle during fat loss","Microgravity creates unique metabolic challenges","Nature Medicine study addresses space health gap"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/obesity-therapy-could-determine-mars-mission-viabi/main.jpg","alt":"Obesity Therapy Could Determine Mars Mission Viability"},"subtitle":"Novi pristup liječenju metaboličkih bolesti u svemiru i na Zemlji","subtitleEn":"The medical constraint behind long-duration mission planning","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/obesity-therapy-could-determine-mars-mission-viabi/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The medical constraint behind long-duration mission planning"},"tags":["space"],"geo":{"name":"Baton Rouge, Louisiana, United States","lat":30.4515,"lon":-91.1871,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$14","part1En":"When we talk about obesity in the context of long-term space missions, the problem stops being aesthetic or even purely medical — it becomes an operational risk. Muscle mass loss in microgravity conditions is already well-documented, and the combination of reduced physical activity and altered metabolism makes maintaining body composition one of the key challenges for future Mars colonies or extended flights. A recent study published in [Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/nm/) addresses this precise concern, demonstrating that combined therapy approaches can reduce fat mass while preserving — and in some cases building — muscle tissue. For mission planners at [NASA](https://www.nasa.gov) and other space agencies, this represents more than a medical advancement; it's a potential solution to one of the most persistent barriers to long-duration human spaceflight. The implications extend beyond individual astronaut health to mission viability itself.","part2En":"$15"},{"id":"2026-03-22-mit-s-injectable-livers-could-transform-transplant","dbId":603,"title":"MIT's Injectable Livers Could Transform Transplant Medicine","titleEn":"MIT's Injectable Livers Could Transform Transplant Medicine","category":"space","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The future of organ transplantation may not require surgery at all.","execSummary":"MIT’s injectable 'satellite livers' challenge the transplant status quo by offering a minimally invasive alternative to organ replacement. This article examines the scientific significance—reducing donor dependency and surgical risks—while framing the unresolved questions (scalability, long-term viability) that will determine whether this becomes a clinical reality or remains a promising experiment.","keyPoints":["MIT engineers create injectable liver cells with protective gel","\"Satellite livers\" may eliminate need for major surgery","Successful tests show functional transplant alternative"],"source":{"name":"NotebookCheck","url":"https://www.notebookcheck.net/Injectable-mini-livers-show-promise-as-transplant-alternative-after-successful-test.1256348.0.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/mit-s-injectable-livers-could-transform-transplant/main.jpg","alt":"MIT's Injectable Livers Could Transform Transplant Medicine"},"subtitle":"Zašto bi ovo moglo promijeniti budućnost transplantologije — i koje su sljedeće prepreke","subtitleEn":"Why this matters for organ replacement","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/mit-s-injectable-livers-could-transform-transplant/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why this matters for organ replacement"},"tags":["Organ Transplantation","Transplantology","Medical Innovation"],"geo":{"name":"Cambridge, Massachusetts, United States","lat":42.3601,"lon":-71.0942,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$16","part1En":"$17","part2En":"$18"},{"id":"2026-03-22-mars-gravity-poses-new-questions-for-astronaut-mus","dbId":596,"title":"Mars Gravity Poses New Questions for Astronaut Muscle Health","titleEn":"Mars Gravity Poses New Questions for Astronaut Muscle Health","category":"space","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Before astronauts set foot on Mars, scientists need to understand what the planet's gravity will do to human bodies.","execSummary":"An international research team led by Marie Mortreux is studying how Mars's lower gravity could severely impact astronauts' skeletal muscles, posing a major challenge for long-term missions. This analysis explores the scientific significance, potential solutions, and what it means for the future of human space exploration beyond Earth orbit.","keyPoints":["URI researcher joins Mars muscle study","International team investigates skeletal adaptation","Research critical for future mission planning"],"source":{"name":"Universe Today","url":"https://www.universetoday.com/articles/how-will-martian-gravity-affect-skeletal-muscle"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/mars-gravity-poses-new-questions-for-astronaut-mus/main.jpg","alt":"Mars Gravity Poses New Questions for Astronaut Muscle Health"},"subtitle":"Utjecaj Marsove gravitacije na ljudsko tijelo: zašto je ovo istraživanje ključno za buduće misije?","subtitleEn":"Why muscle matters for Mars missions","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/mars-gravity-poses-new-questions-for-astronaut-mus/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why muscle matters for Mars missions"},"tags":["Mars Mission","Astronaut Health","Space Exploration"],"geo":{"name":"Rhode Island, USA","lat":41.7423,"lon":-71.7601,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$19","part1En":"Before astronauts set foot on Mars, scientists need to understand what the planet's gravity will do to human bodies. Marie Mortreux, an assistant professor at the [University of Rhode Island's College of Health Sciences](https://uri.edu/), has joined an international research team investigating how Mars's gravitational environment would affect astronauts' skeletal muscle. The research, [reported by Universe Today](https://www.universetoday.com/), addresses a physiological question that grows more urgent as Mars missions move from aspiration to active planning.\nThe stakes are considerable. At roughly 38% of Earth's gravity, Mars presents an environment that human physiology has never encountered. Studies from the International Space Station have documented severe muscle atrophy in microgravity, but Mars gravity represents an entirely different challenge. Neither full weightlessness nor Earth-normal, it exists in a physiological gray zone that demands dedicated investigation.","part2En":"$1a"},{"id":"2026-03-20-blue-origin-s-51-600-satellite-plan-for-orbital-ai","dbId":555,"title":"Blue Origin's 51,600-Satellite Plan for Orbital AI","titleEn":"Blue Origin's 51,600-Satellite Plan for Orbital AI","category":"space","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Blue Origin has filed with the Federal Communications Commission to deploy 51,600 satellites under a project called Sunrise — a proposal that would create an orbital data center designed specifically for artificial intelligence processing.","execSummary":"Blue Origin plans to launch 51,600 satellites for an orbital AI data center, potentially shifting computing power to space. This initiative could redefine space infrastructure, but raises questions about coordination, capacity, and long-term impact on space exploration and technology.","keyPoints":["Blue Origin files for massive satellite constellation","Project Sunrise targets orbital AI data centers","Sun-synchronous orbits between 311-1,118 miles altitude"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/blue-origin-s-51-600-satellite-plan-for-orbital-ai/main.jpg","alt":"Blue Origin's 51,600-Satellite Plan for Orbital AI"},"subtitle":"Zašto Project Sunrise nije samo još jedna konstelacija","subtitleEn":"What Sunrise means for orbital infrastructure","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/blue-origin-s-51-600-satellite-plan-for-orbital-ai/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What Sunrise means for orbital infrastructure"},"tags":["Blue Origin","Project Sunrise","Satellite Constellation"],"geo":{"name":"Kent, Washington, United States","lat":47.380933,"lon":-122.234889,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$1b","part1En":"Blue Origin has filed with the Federal Communications Commission to deploy 51,600 satellites under a project called Sunrise — a proposal that would create an orbital data center designed specifically for artificial intelligence processing. The filing represents one of the largest satellite constellation proposals ever submitted to U.S. regulators, a scale that demands attention even before hardware exists.\nThe significance here isn't spectacle. It's infrastructure. According to the filing, these satellites would operate in sun-synchronous orbits between 311 and 1,118 miles altitude, with layers spaced 3 to 6 miles apart. Each orbital layer would contain between 300 and 1,000 satellites working in coordinated clusters. The goal is positioning computing power where latency advantages exist and where terrestrial constraints — cooling, power, physical real estate — become manageable variables rather than hard limits.","part2En":"$1c"},{"id":"2026-03-20-ohios-7-ton-meteorite-a-rare-delivery-from-the-sol","dbId":552,"title":"Ohio’s 7-ton meteorite: A rare delivery from the solar system’s past","titleEn":"Ohio’s 7-ton meteorite: A rare delivery from the solar system’s past","category":"space","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When a 7-ton space rock [exploded over Ohio](https://fireballs.","execSummary":"The 7-ton Ohio meteorite isn’t just a visual spectacle—it’s a direct sample of the early solar system’s building blocks. This article cuts through the spectacle to explain why its fragments matter for planetary science, how recovery efforts are coordinated, and what unanswered questions linger about asteroid composition and Earth’s origins.","keyPoints":["One of the largest tracked meteorite falls in years","NASA’s fireball network confirms rare carbonaceous chondrite potential","Fragments could hold clues to early solar system chemistry"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/ohios-7-ton-meteorite-a-rare-delivery-from-the-sol/main.jpg","alt":"Ohio’s 7-ton meteorite: A rare delivery from the solar system’s past"},"subtitle":"Od spektakla do znanosti: Kako se iz meteora izvlači vrijedna informacija","subtitleEn":"The fireball over Ohio wasn’t just a spectacle—it was a 7-ton time capsule hurtling toward Earth at 46,000 mph. Here’s why scientists are racing to recover it.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/ohios-7-ton-meteorite-a-rare-delivery-from-the-sol/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The fireball over Ohio wasn’t just a spectacle—it was a 7-ton time capsule hurtling toward Earth at 46,000 mph. Here’s why scientists are racing to recover it."},"tags":["Meteorite","Ohio","Planetary Science"],"geo":{"name":"San Francisco, US","lat":37.7749,"lon":-122.4194,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$1d","part1En":"$1e","part2En":"$1f"},{"id":"2026-03-20-biodegradable-robot-finger-turns-to-soil","dbId":541,"title":"Biodegradable Robot Finger Turns to Soil","titleEn":"Biodegradable Robot Finger Turns to Soil","category":"space","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The global electronic waste crisis has found an unlikely ally: a robotic finger designed to disappear.","execSummary":"The first fully biodegradable robotic actuator isn’t just an eco-gimmick—it’s a direct response to the unaddressed problem of space debris *on* other planets. Cornell’s gelatine-cellulose composite could redefine mission sustainability by eliminating permanent waste, but scalability and extreme-environment durability remain untested. The real question: should this become the default for all future off-world hardware?","keyPoints":["Fully compostable robotic finger developed","Dissolves safely into nutrient-rich soil","Response to global electronic waste crisis"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/biodegradable-robot-finger-turns-to-soil/main.jpg","alt":"Biodegradable Robot Finger Turns to Soil"},"subtitle":"Zašto bi svaki budući rover trebao moći nestati u tlu?","subtitleEn":"Why durability and decay belong together","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/biodegradable-robot-finger-turns-to-soil/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why durability and decay belong together"},"tags":["Space Debris","Biodegradable Robotics","Planetary Rover"],"geo":{"name":"Ithaca, United States","lat":42.4534,"lon":-76.4735,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$20","part1En":"$21","part2En":"$22"},{"id":"2026-03-20-canada-s-200m-spaceport-bet-a-sovereignty-play","dbId":540,"title":"Canada's $200M Spaceport Bet: A Sovereignty Play","titleEn":"Canada's $200M Spaceport Bet: A Sovereignty Play","category":"space","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Canada has officially entered the commercial space race.","execSummary":"Canada’s $200M investment in Nova Scotia’s first commercial spaceport isn’t just about launch infrastructure—it’s a strategic move toward orbital autonomy. By reducing reliance on foreign launch sites, Canada gains control over satellite deployment timelines, critical for Arctic monitoring and scientific missions. The real test will be whether Maritime Launch Services can deliver on cost competitiveness and operational reliability by the 2025 target.","keyPoints":["$$200 million federal investment confirmed","Nova Scotia hosts first commercial spaceport","Maritime Launch Services to operate facility"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/canada-s-200m-spaceport-bet-a-sovereignty-play/main.jpg","alt":"Canada's $200M Spaceport Bet: A Sovereignty Play"},"subtitle":"Zašto ovo nije samo o lansiranju raketa, već o strategijskoj autonomiji","subtitleEn":"Why launch capability matters now","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/canada-s-200m-spaceport-bet-a-sovereignty-play/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why launch capability matters now"},"tags":["Canada","Spaceport","Nova Scotia"],"geo":{"name":"Canso, Nova Scotia, Canada","lat":45.35,"lon":-61.0167,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$23","part1En":"$24","part2En":"$25"},{"id":"2026-03-20-cotton-candy-worlds-defy-jwst-behind-impenetrable-","dbId":538,"title":"Cotton Candy Worlds Defy JWST Behind Impenetrable Haze","titleEn":"Cotton Candy Worlds Defy JWST Behind Impenetrable Haze","category":"space","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The James Webb Space Telescope, humanity's most powerful eye on the cosmos, has met an unexpected adversary: a layer of impenetrable haze surrounding some of the strangest worlds ever discovered.","execSummary":"The discovery that Webb cannot penetrate the haze around ultra-low-density 'cotton candy' exoplanets forces a reckoning with observational limits—not just for this telescope, but for exoplanet science as a whole. The article examines why this matters beyond spectacle: it exposes a blind spot in atmospheric study methods and demands rethinking of future mission designs.","keyPoints":["Ultra-low-density exoplanets among least dense ever found","James Webb Telescope blocked by mysterious atmospheric smog","All atmospheric probing attempts have failed"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/cotton-candy-worlds-defy-jwst-behind-impenetrable-/main.jpg","alt":"Cotton Candy Worlds Defy JWST Behind Impenetrable Haze"},"subtitle":"Zašto je ovo više od samo 'zanimljive anomalije' — i kako mijenja planove za buduća promatranja","subtitleEn":"What remains hidden when our best instruments fall short","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/cotton-candy-worlds-defy-jwst-behind-impenetrable-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What remains hidden when our best instruments fall short"},"tags":["Exoplanets","Webb Space Telescope","Space Observation"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$26","part1En":"$27","part2En":"$28"},{"id":"2026-03-19-spin-speed-finally-separates-giant-planets-from-br","dbId":510,"title":"Spin speed finally separates giant planets from brown dwarfs","titleEn":"Spin speed finally separates giant planets from brown dwarfs","category":"space","date":"2026-03-19T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-19T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For four decades, astronomers have faced an infuriating ambiguity: when peering through telescopes, the line between a [giant exoplanet](https://exoplanets.","execSummary":"Northwestern University's discovery that spin speed distinguishes giant planets from brown dwarfs resolves a decades-old classification challenge. This operational metric simplifies identification without complex spectroscopy, with implications for formation theories and future telescope missions like JWST.","keyPoints":["Spin rates distinguish planets from failed stars","Decades-old classification problem gets a solution","What this means for exoplanet and stellar formation"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/spin-speed-finally-separates-giant-planets-from-br/main.jpg","alt":"Spin speed finally separates giant planets from brown dwarfs"},"subtitle":"Razumijevanje svemirskih tijela na granici planeta i zvijezda","subtitleEn":"A 40-year puzzle solved—not by composition, but by rotation.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/spin-speed-finally-separates-giant-planets-from-br/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A 40-year puzzle solved—not by composition, but by rotation."},"tags":["Exoplanets","Brown Dwarfs","Planetary Formation"],"geo":{"name":"Evanston, United States","lat":42.0451,"lon":-87.6877,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$29","part1En":"$2a","part2En":"$2b"},{"id":"2026-03-17-moon-bases-need-room-to-growliterally-heres-the-be","dbId":446,"title":"Moon bases need room to grow—literally. Here’s the bet on it.","titleEn":"Moon bases need room to grow—literally. Here’s the bet on it.","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The moon’s surface isn’t just barren; it’s *expensive*.","execSummary":"Voyager Technologies' multi-million dollar investment in Max Space signals a strategic push to solve NASA’s Artemis program’s critical bottleneck: how to transport and deploy enough habitable volume for sustained lunar presence. The article analyzes why expandable habitats—offering up to 3x more space post-deployment—could redefine mission logistics, while noting unresolved challenges like regolith abrasion and NASA’s parallel evaluations of competing designs.","keyPoints":["Voyager’s multi-million bet on expandable lunar habitats","Artemis timeline demands lightweight, scalable moon bases","Expandables: proven in orbit, untested on the lunar surface"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/moon-bases-need-room-to-growliterally-heres-the-be/main.jpg","alt":"Moon bases need room to grow—literally. Here’s the bet on it."},"subtitle":"Zašto bi upravo ova tehnologija mogla odrediti budućnost ljudskog boravka na Mjesecu","subtitleEn":"The quiet race to solve NASA’s most practical moon problem: where astronauts will live—and how much it will weigh to get there.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/moon-bases-need-room-to-growliterally-heres-the-be/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The quiet race to solve NASA’s most practical moon problem: where astronauts will live—and how much it will weigh to get there."},"tags":["NASA","Lunar Base","Space Exploration"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$2c","part1En":"$2d","part2En":"$2e"},{"id":"2026-03-17-rfx-fuse-revives-breimans-lost-vision-for-machine-","dbId":444,"title":"RFX-Fuse Revives Breiman’s Lost Vision for Machine Learning","titleEn":"RFX-Fuse Revives Breiman’s Lost Vision for Machine Learning","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"In 2001, Leo Breiman and Adele Cutler designed [Random Forests](https://link.","execSummary":"RFX-Fuse revives Breiman and Cutler’s original Random Forest vision as a *true* unified ML engine—classification, similarity, outlier detection, and more in a single model. For scientific missions (e.g., satellite data analysis), this reduces toolchain fragmentation by 60-80%, but the real test is whether its integrated approach sacrifices rigor for convenience. The bigger question: Can consolidated models change how we design exploration pipelines?","keyPoints":["Unified ML engine replaces 5+ fragmented tools","Native GPU/CPU support for full Random Forest capabilities","Scikit-learn never implemented the original design"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/rfx-fuse-revives-breimans-lost-vision-for-machine-/main.jpg","alt":"RFX-Fuse Revives Breiman’s Lost Vision for Machine Learning"},"subtitle":"Zašto je unifikirani ML engine važan za znanstvenu eksploraciju podataka","subtitleEn":"One model object where modern pipelines need a toolchain","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/rfx-fuse-revives-breimans-lost-vision-for-machine-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"One model object where modern pipelines need a toolchain"},"tags":["RFX-Fuse","Machine Learning Engine","Space Data Exploration"],"geo":{"name":"Santa Clara, CA","lat":37.3875,"lon":-122.0575,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$2f","part1En":"$30","part2En":"$31"},{"id":"2026-03-17-moons-patchy-magnetism-finally-explained-after-60-","dbId":441,"title":"Moon’s patchy magnetism finally explained after 60 years","titleEn":"Moon’s patchy magnetism finally explained after 60 years","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For six decades, planetary scientists have puzzled over the moon’s magnetic quirks: a near-global absence of a protective field, yet isolated regions where magnetization spikes to ten times the background strength.","execSummary":"This article explains why the Moon's localized magnetic anomalies—up to 10x stronger than background levels—matter beyond scientific curiosity: they reveal Earth-Moon interactions from 4 billion years ago and have direct implications for Artemis mission safety. The focus is on operational significance, not spectacle.","keyPoints":["Solar wind sculpts the moon’s magnetic anomalies","Decades-old lunar mystery tied to crustal iron","Implications for future crewed missions and dust control"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/moons-patchy-magnetism-finally-explained-after-60-/main.jpg","alt":"Moon’s patchy magnetism finally explained after 60 years"},"subtitle":"Zašto su lokalne magnetne ’oaze’ ključne za buduće misije — i što nam još nedostaje","subtitleEn":"A quiet discovery with outsized consequences for exploration","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/moons-patchy-magnetism-finally-explained-after-60-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A quiet discovery with outsized consequences for exploration"},"tags":["Moon Exploration","Lunar Magnetism","Space Mission Planning"],"geo":{"name":"San Francisco, US","lat":37.7749,"lon":-122.4194,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$32","part1En":"$33","part2En":"$34"},{"id":"2026-03-17-how-photonic-ski-jumps-could-rewrite-spacecraft-de","dbId":439,"title":"How ‘Photonic Ski-Jumps’ Could Rewrite Spacecraft Design","titleEn":"How ‘Photonic Ski-Jumps’ Could Rewrite Spacecraft Design","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Every gram launched into orbit is a negotiation.","execSummary":"The article examines how MIT's 'photonic ski-jump' LiDAR technology could eliminate mechanical mirrors in spacecraft systems, drastically reducing SWaP constraints. It contextualizes this within NASA/ESA's push for solid-state solutions and explores operational implications for lunar/Mars missions, while clearly distinguishing confirmed lab results from speculative field performance.","keyPoints":["LiDAR shrinks from mirrors to microchips","SWaP tradeoffs redefined for deep-space missions","MIT-Sandia collaboration targets laser comms bottleneck"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/how-photonic-ski-jumps-could-rewrite-spacecraft-de/main.jpg","alt":"How ‘Photonic Ski-Jumps’ Could Rewrite Spacecraft Design"},"subtitle":"Zašto bi ova tehnologija mogla promijeniti način kako svemirska letjelica ‘gleda’ i komunicira","subtitleEn":"A 50-year problem in optical systems may have just met its match—no moving parts required.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/how-photonic-ski-jumps-could-rewrite-spacecraft-de/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A 50-year problem in optical systems may have just met its match—no moving parts required."},"tags":["LiDAR","Spacecraft Navigation","Microscopy"],"geo":{"name":"Cambridge, MA, USA","lat":42.3601,"lon":-71.0942,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$35","part1En":"$36","part2En":"$37"},{"id":"2026-03-17-universe-may-be-expanding-slower-than-we-thought","dbId":436,"title":"Universe May Be Expanding Slower Than We Thought","titleEn":"Universe May Be Expanding Slower Than We Thought","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The Hubble tension has haunted cosmology for years—a stubborn gap between two methods of measuring how fast our universe expands.","execSummary":"New data suggests the local universe may expand slower than prior estimates, easing the Hubble tension—a key discrepancy in cosmology. This article examines why the adjustment matters for fundamental physics, which missions will verify it next, and what it implies for dark energy models.","keyPoints":["Local expansion rate falls below earlier estimates","Hubble tension gap may finally be narrowing","Cosmic distance calculations face rigorous recheck"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/universe-may-be-expanding-slower-than-we-thought/main.jpg","alt":"Universe May Be Expanding Slower Than We Thought"},"subtitle":"Novi pristup razumijevanju brzine širenja svemira","subtitleEn":"What the numbers actually mean","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/universe-may-be-expanding-slower-than-we-thought/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the numbers actually mean"},"tags":["Hubble Constant","Cosmic Expansion","Dark Energy"],"geo":{"name":"Houston, TX","lat":29.5502,"lon":-95.097,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$38","part1En":"$39","part2En":"$3a"},{"id":"2026-03-17-jwst-discovers-new-exoplanet-class-with-distinctiv","dbId":434,"title":"JWST Discovers New Exoplanet Class with Distinctive Chemistry","titleEn":"JWST Discovers New Exoplanet Class with Distinctive Chemistry","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The James Webb Space Telescope has identified what astronomers are calling a new class of exoplanet, according to [Space.","execSummary":"The discovery of sulfur dioxide in HD 189733 b’s atmosphere via JWST isn’t about sensationalism—it’s a critical data point challenging planetary formation models. This article frames why sulfur chemistry matters for exoplanet science and what operational shifts it demands from upcoming missions like Ariel.","keyPoints":["JWST identifies new exoplanet category","Atmospheric chemistry drives classification","Observation demonstrates telescope capabilities"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/jwst-discovers-new-exoplanet-class-with-distinctiv/main.jpg","alt":"JWST Discovers New Exoplanet Class with Distinctive Chemistry"},"subtitle":"Zašto je otkriće neobičnog sastava važnije od senzacionalizma o 'smradu'","subtitleEn":"What the data actually confirms","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/jwst-discovers-new-exoplanet-class-with-distinctiv/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the data actually confirms"},"tags":["Exoplanet","Atmospheric Composition","Space Discovery"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$3b","part1En":"The James Webb Space Telescope has identified what astronomers are calling a new class of exoplanet, according to [Space.com](https://www.space.com). This matters not because of the unusual characterization that the planet \"probably smells like rotten eggs,\" but because JWST's instruments have detected atmospheric signatures distinctive enough to warrant an entirely new classification category. The discovery represents a significant milestone in [JWST's exoplanet characterization mission](https://www.nasa.gov/webb), demonstrating the telescope's capacity to analyze atmospheric compositions with precision that was simply impossible before its deployment. Early signals suggest the presence of sulfur compounds, which would explain the pungent comparison, though researchers have not yet confirmed the exact molecular makeup. What's notable here is the methodical approach. This wasn't a serendipitous find but the result of systematic atmospheric analysis that JWST was specifically designed to conduct.","part2En":"$3c"},{"id":"2026-03-17-ryugu-samples-hold-life-s-full-genetic-toolkit","dbId":433,"title":"Ryugu Samples Hold Life's Full Genetic Toolkit","titleEn":"Ryugu Samples Hold Life's Full Genetic Toolkit","category":"space","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Scientists confirmed Monday that samples from asteroid Ryugu contain all five nucleobases—the fundamental building blocks of DNA and RNA.","execSummary":"The discovery of all DNA/RNA nucleobases in Ryugu samples shifts the origin-of-life debate from speculation to measurable chemistry. This article frames why uncontaminated asteroid material matters more than meteorite finds, and what JAXA’s Hayabusa2 mission tells us about the resilience of life’s building blocks in space.","keyPoints":["All five nucleobases found in asteroid samples","Chain of custody eliminates contamination concerns","Discovery reframes life's origins question"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/ryugu-samples-hold-life-s-full-genetic-toolkit/main.jpg","alt":"Ryugu Samples Hold Life's Full Genetic Toolkit"},"subtitle":"Zašto je ovo više od još jednog svemirskog otkrića: naučna preciznost umjesto spektakla","subtitleEn":"Why completeness matters more than spectacle","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/ryugu-samples-hold-life-s-full-genetic-toolkit/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why completeness matters more than spectacle"},"tags":["Ryugu","Asteroid Sample Return","Organic Matter","Hayabusa2","Astrobiology"],"geo":{"name":"Sagamihara, Japan","lat":35.5631,"lon":139.3822,"countryCode":"JP"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$3d","part1En":"Scientists confirmed Monday that samples from asteroid Ryugu contain all five nucleobases—the fundamental building blocks of DNA and RNA. This isn't another tantalizing hint or partial detection. It's the complete set, recovered intact from a pristine carbon-rich asteroid that hasn't changed much since the solar system formed 4.5 billion years ago. The [Hayabusa2 mission](https://global.jaxa.jp/projects/sats/hayabusa2/) delivered these samples to Earth in 2020, after a journey of over 300 million kilometers. But analysis continues to yield results that reframe how we think about life's origins. What makes this finding significant isn't spectacle—it's completeness. Previous meteorite discoveries showed some nucleobases, but terrestrial contamination always clouded the interpretation. Ryugu's samples were collected in space, sealed in pristine containers, and returned without ever touching Earth's surface. The chain of custody is unbroken, which means the confidence level is unusually high.","part2En":"The implications extend beyond confirming that organic chemistry operates consistently beyond Earth. If asteroids like Ryugu carried the full genetic toolkit to early Earth, the bottleneck for abiogenesis shifts from \"where do the ingredients come from?\" to \"how do they assemble themselves?\" That's a fundamentally different scientific question—and arguably a more tractable one. The [discovery](https://phys.org/news/2023-ryugu-asteroid-dna-rna-blocks.html) supports the theory that life's chemistry isn't uniquely terrestrial but rather a process the universe runs wherever conditions permit. What remains uncertain is whether these nucleobases formed on Ryugu itself or were delivered by even older cosmic processes. The research team at [JAXA](https://global.jaxa.jp/) and partner institutions continues analyzing sample composition, searching for concentration patterns and isotopic signatures that might answer that question."},{"id":"2026-03-16-perovskites-quiet-leap-why-flexible-solar-cells-ma","dbId":423,"title":"Perovskite’s quiet leap: Why flexible solar cells matter for space","titleEn":"Perovskite’s quiet leap: Why flexible solar cells matter for space","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When the European Space Agency’s [Juice probe](https://www.","execSummary":"TNO’s Perovion Technologies is betting on roll-to-roll perovskite solar cells to solve a critical space challenge: lightweight, flexible power for missions where rigid panels fail. The 2030 factory plan isn’t just industrial scaling—it’s a test of whether perovskite can endure space’s harsh conditions, with implications for lunar bases, long-duration satellites, and the broader shift toward in-situ resource utilization.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/perovskites-quiet-leap-why-flexible-solar-cells-ma/main.jpg","alt":"Perovskite’s quiet leap: Why flexible solar cells matter for space"},"subtitle":"Kad je Sunčeva svjetlost resurs, a težina neprijatelj — perovskit postaje ključni saveznik","subtitleEn":"The first factory of its kind won’t just make solar cells. It will test whether perovskites can outlast silicon where it counts.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/perovskites-quiet-leap-why-flexible-solar-cells-ma/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The first factory of its kind won’t just make solar cells. It will test whether perovskites can outlast silicon where it counts."},"tags":["Perovskite","Solar Panels","Space Exploration"],"geo":{"name":"Eindhoven, Netherlands","lat":51.4416,"lon":5.4697,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$3e","part1En":"$3f","part2En":"$40"},{"id":"2026-03-16-starcloud-seeks-fcc-nod-for-88-000-satellite-data-","dbId":400,"title":"Starcloud Seeks FCC Nod for 88,000-Satellite Data Center Constellation","titleEn":"Starcloud Seeks FCC Nod for 88,000-Satellite Data Center Constellation","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The mathematics alone demand attention: 88,000 satellites would more than triple the total number of objects currently tracked in Earth orbit.","execSummary":"Starcloud's proposed 88,000-satellite constellation isn't just a scale record—it's a test case for orbital data centers as infrastructure and a stress test for LEO governance. The article dissects why this matters beyond spectacle: regulatory gaps, scientific risks, and the shift from ground-based to space-based computing, framing it as a pivot point for space economy rules.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/starcloud-seeks-fcc-nod-for-88-000-satellite-data-/main.jpg","alt":"Starcloud Seeks FCC Nod for 88,000-Satellite Data Center Constellation"},"subtitle":"Kontekst u dvije rečenice: od podataka do orbite, od ambicije do regulatornih izazova","subtitleEn":"Why scale matters here","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/starcloud-seeks-fcc-nod-for-88-000-satellite-data-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why scale matters here"},"tags":["Starcloud","Satellite Constellation","Low Earth Orbit","Data Center"],"geo":{"name":"Redmond, WA","lat":47.6739,"lon":-122.1214,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$41","part1En":"$42","part2En":"$43"},{"id":"2026-03-16-the-xbox-one-jailbreak-a-victory-for-digital-prese","dbId":395,"title":"The Xbox One Jailbreak: A Victory for Digital Preservation","titleEn":"The Xbox One Jailbreak: A Victory for Digital Preservation","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Thirteen years after its commercial debut, the original Xbox One has finally yielded to persistent researchers, a milestone that transcends mere gaming nostalgia.","execSummary":"The jailbreak of the original Xbox One via voltage glitching isn’t just a gaming curiosity—it’s a case study in hardware longevity and security vulnerabilities. By bypassing boot ROM protections, researchers expose how aging electronics become both more fragile and more exploitable, with direct implications for digital preservation, embedded systems in space missions, and the ethics of post-support device ownership.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/the-xbox-one-jailbreak-a-victory-for-digital-prese/main.jpg","alt":"The Xbox One Jailbreak: A Victory for Digital Preservation"},"subtitle":"Kontekst u dvije rečenice: od igračke konzole do laboratorija za istraživanje trajnosti elektronike","subtitleEn":"Voltage glitching bypasses boot ROM security after 13 years","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/the-xbox-one-jailbreak-a-victory-for-digital-prese/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Voltage glitching bypasses boot ROM security after 13 years"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Redmond, United States","lat":47.678,"lon":-122.1303,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$44","part1En":"$45","part2En":"$46"},{"id":"2026-03-16-senate-mandates-a-moon-base-nasa-s-2030-deadline-g","dbId":393,"title":"Senate Mandates a Moon Base: NASA's 2030 Deadline Gets Real","titleEn":"Senate Mandates a Moon Base: NASA's 2030 Deadline Gets Real","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The United States Senate has done something quietly significant: it has transformed NASA's lunar aspirations from strategic visions into a legislative directive.","execSummary":"NASA’s 2030 lunar base isn’t just a return to the Moon—it’s a strategic shift to turn Earth’s satellite into a operational hub for deep-space survival testing. The Senate’s directive formalizes this as policy, but funding, radiation protection, and international roles remain unresolved. The real stakes? Proving whether humans can live beyond Earth’s orbit before attempting Mars.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/senate-mandates-a-moon-base-nasa-s-2030-deadline-g/main.jpg","alt":"Senate Mandates a Moon Base: NASA's 2030 Deadline Gets Real"},"subtitle":"Od senatskog naloga do prvih modula: kronologija odluke i što slijedi u sljedećih sedam godina","subtitleEn":"From Legislative Text to Lunar Dust","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/senate-mandates-a-moon-base-nasa-s-2030-deadline-g/subtitle.jpg","alt":"From Legislative Text to Lunar Dust"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Mjesec (Moon), Outer Space","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$47","part1En":"$48","part2En":"$49"},{"id":"2026-03-16-chaos-eclipses-physics-in-neutron-star-simulations","dbId":388,"title":"Chaos Eclipses Physics in Neutron Star Simulations","titleEn":"Chaos Eclipses Physics in Neutron Star Simulations","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When the most violent mergers in the universe occur, chaos does not merely accompany the event; it actively suppresses the very laws of physics we rely on to understand them.","execSummary":"This article reframes neutron star mergers not as spectacular explosions but as critical tests of physics at its limits—where even light gets trapped. The angle focuses on why supercomputers are the only tool capable of unpacking this chaos, and what that means for our understanding of element formation, general relativity, and future gravitational-wave astronomy.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/chaos-eclipses-physics-in-neutron-star-simulations/main.jpg","alt":"Chaos Eclipses Physics in Neutron Star Simulations"},"subtitle":"Zašto je ovo važno: bez superračunala, čitav proces ostaje nevidljiv","subtitleEn":"Why supercomputer models now show disorder overriding fundamental laws","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/chaos-eclipses-physics-in-neutron-star-simulations/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why supercomputer models now show disorder overriding fundamental laws"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$4a","part1En":"When the most violent mergers in the universe occur, chaos does not merely accompany the event; it actively suppresses the very laws of physics we rely on to understand them. New supercomputer simulations reveal that during neutron star collisions, magnetic fields become so turbulent that they trap high-energy gamma-ray photons, preventing them from escaping the immediate aftermath. This finding shifts our understanding from viewing these events as simple laboratories for nuclear physics to recognizing them as domains where disorder dictates observable reality. For astrophysicists, this means previous models assuming clean photon emission may need significant recalibration to account for this entrapment. The significance lies not in the spectacle of the crash, but in the realization that our standard physical models break down under such extreme magnetic stress. You can read the initial report from [Universe Today](https://www.universetoday.com) regarding these extraordinary events.","part2En":"The simulations indicate that the magnetic turbulence generates a chaotic environment where photon paths are randomized rather than directed. This suggests that what we observe from Earth might only be a fraction of the actual energy released, as much of it remains locked within the merger's core. Researchers are now cross-referencing these computational results with historical data from gamma-ray burst detectors to see if this 'trapping' effect explains certain anomalies in light curves. While the community is responding with cautious optimism, early signals suggest this is a computational artifact that mirrors physical reality, not just a modeling error. Further peer review is required before this becomes a confirmed constraint on high-energy astrophysics, but the implications for how we model the early universe are profound. Detailed analysis of the magnetic topology is available via [simulations discussed here](https://www.universetoday.com)."},{"id":"2026-03-16-artemis-2-clears-final-hurdle-for-april-moon-missi","dbId":376,"title":"Artemis 2 Clears Final Hurdle for April Moon Mission","titleEn":"Artemis 2 Clears Final Hurdle for April Moon Mission","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The completion of the [flight readiness review](https://www.","execSummary":"NASA's Artemis 2 mission, set for April 1, marks the first crewed lunar flyby in 50 years—but its real significance lies in testing deep-space survival tech for Mars. This analysis cuts through the spectacle to examine the mission's scientific stakes, political risks, and the unanswered question: Is this a sustainable step toward interplanetary travel, or an expensive dead end?","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/artemis-2-clears-final-hurdle-for-april-moon-missi/main.jpg","alt":"Artemis 2 Clears Final Hurdle for April Moon Mission"},"subtitle":"Tri razloga zašto ova misija mijenja pravila svemirskog istraživanja","subtitleEn":"Why this flyby defines the next half-century of spaceflight","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/artemis-2-clears-final-hurdle-for-april-moon-missi/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why this flyby defines the next half-century of spaceflight"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Houston, TX, USA","lat":29.7604,"lon":-95.3698,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$4b","part1En":"$4c","part2En":"$4d"},{"id":"2026-03-16-a-battery-built-for-deep-space","dbId":360,"title":"A Battery Built for Deep Space","titleEn":"A Battery Built for Deep Space","category":"space","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The significance of a new battery isn't measured in minutes saved at a charging station, but in kilometers unlocked on a distant world.","execSummary":"A new lithium-metal battery technology achieves a breakthrough in charging speed (15 minutes) and energy density (1,747.6 W/kg), solving long-standing safety and efficiency issues. This advancement matters because it could revolutionize space exploration by enabling missions with greater autonomy and faster recharge cycles, addressing critical limitations in current energy storage for spacecraft and rovers. The key question is whether this technology can scale beyond the lab and redefine what's possible in both electric vehicles and deep-space missions.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/a-battery-built-for-deep-space/main.jpg","alt":"A Battery Built for Deep Space"},"subtitle":"Zašto je nova litij-metalna tehnologija prekretnica za istraživanje svemira i elektromobilnost","subtitleEn":"From lab to launchpad: the timeline of a power breakthrough","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/a-battery-built-for-deep-space/subtitle.jpg","alt":"From lab to launchpad: the timeline of a power breakthrough"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$4e","part1En":"$4f","part2En":"$50"},{"id":"2026-03-12-darts-kinetic-nudge-proves-planetary-defense-isnt-","dbId":258,"title":"DART’s kinetic nudge proves planetary defense isn’t science fiction","titleEn":"DART’s kinetic nudge proves planetary defense isn’t science fiction","category":"space","date":"2026-03-12T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-12T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For the first time in history, humanity has deliberately changed the trajectory of a celestial object.","execSummary":"NASA's DART mission didn't just hit an asteroid—it proved kinetic impact can alter orbital paths, creating a measurable change in both Dimorphos and its parent asteroid Didymos. This shifts planetary defense from theory to practice, but also raises questions about long-term cosmic consequences and the need for international protocols. The focus is on operational implications and the scientific threshold crossed, not spectacle.","source":{"name":"Future Pulse","url":"https://futurepulse.hr"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/darts-kinetic-nudge-proves-planetary-defense-isnt-/main.jpg","alt":"DART’s kinetic nudge proves planetary defense isn’t science fiction"},"subtitle":"Od eksperimenta do planetarne obrane: što nam govore prvi podaci o promjeni putanje","subtitleEn":"A 22-minute orbital shift and 10,000 tons of debris later, what the data actually tells us","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/darts-kinetic-nudge-proves-planetary-defense-isnt-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A 22-minute orbital shift and 10,000 tons of debris later, what the data actually tells us"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Laurel, Maryland, United States","lat":39.0987,"lon":-76.8506,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$51","part1En":"$52","part2En":"$53"},{"id":"2026-03-12-a-cosmic-collision-reveals-how-gold-and-platinum-a","dbId":249,"title":"A cosmic collision reveals how gold and platinum are forged","titleEn":"A cosmic collision reveals how gold and platinum are forged","category":"space","date":"2026-03-12T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-12T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When a flash of gamma rays pierced the cosmos last September, it carried more than just energy—it carried answers.","execSummary":"The detection of GRB 230906A — a gamma-ray burst linked to a neutron star collision — provides the first direct evidence that such events forge the universe’s heaviest elements (gold, platinum). This article explains why this shifts our understanding of cosmic chemical evolution and outlines the next steps: targeted searches in galaxy merger zones, JWST follow-ups, and the role of next-gen gravitational wave detectors in confirming the r-process theory.","source":{"name":"Future Pulse","url":"https://futurepulse.hr"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/a-cosmic-collision-reveals-how-gold-and-platinum-a/main.jpg","alt":"A cosmic collision reveals how gold and platinum are forged"},"subtitle":"Kako 15-sekundni gama-bljesak mijenja naše razumijevanje nastanka metala","subtitleEn":"The wreckage of two neutron stars, 100 million years in the making","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/a-cosmic-collision-reveals-how-gold-and-platinum-a/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The wreckage of two neutron stars, 100 million years in the making"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"San Francisco, US","lat":37.7749,"lon":-122.4194,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$54","part1En":"$55","part2En":"$56"},{"id":"2026-03-11-nasa-detects-a-star-collision-where-none-should-ex","dbId":245,"title":"NASA detects a star collision where none should exist","titleEn":"NASA detects a star collision where none should exist","category":"space","date":"2026-03-11T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-11T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For the first time, astronomers have observed what appears to be the collision of two ultradense stars—not in the vast, empty reaches of intergalactic space, nor in a sprawling spiral galaxy, but in a tiny, gas-choked dwarf system where such events were thought exceedingly rare.","execSummary":"NASA's detection of a neutron star collision in an unexpected low-metallicity dwarf galaxy challenges existing models of heavy element formation and kilonova occurrence. The discovery suggests that rare earth elements may form in a wider range of cosmic environments than previously thought, with direct implications for future gravitational wave and X-ray observatories.","source":{"name":"Future Pulse","url":"https://futurepulse.hr"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/nasa-detects-a-star-collision-where-none-should-ex/main.jpg","alt":"NASA detects a star collision where none should exist"},"subtitle":"Događaj u neočekivanoj galaktičkoj okolini može razjasniti dvije velike astrofizičke zagonetke","subtitleEn":"A violent merger in a gas-shrouded dwarf galaxy challenges two cosmic puzzles at once","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/nasa-detects-a-star-collision-where-none-should-ex/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A violent merger in a gas-shrouded dwarf galaxy challenges two cosmic puzzles at once"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$57","part1En":"$58","part2En":"$59"},{"id":"2026-03-11-turbulent-plasma-hides-signals","dbId":198,"title":"Turbulent Plasma Hides Signals","category":"space","date":"2026-03-11T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-11T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A new study by researchers at the SETI Institute suggests that stellar 'space weather' could make radio signals from extraterrestrial intelligence harder to detect.","source":{"name":"Future Pulse","url":"https://futurepulse.hr"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/turbulent-plasma-hides-signals/main.jpg","alt":"Turbulent Plasma Hides Signals"},"subtitle":"Why stellar space weather matters for technosignature detection","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/turbulent-plasma-hides-signals/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why stellar space weather matters for technosignature detection"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Mountain View, United States","lat":37.3861,"lon":-122.0839,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$5a"},{"id":"2026-03-10-turbulent-plasma-hides-signals","dbId":198,"title":"Turbulent Plasma Hides Signals","titleEn":"Turbulent Plasma Hides Signals","category":"space","date":"2026-03-10T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-10T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A new study by researchers at the SETI Institute suggests that stellar 'space weather' could make radio signals from extraterrestrial intelligence harder to detect.","execSummary":"The study reveals how stellar plasma turbulence can distort narrowband extraterrestrial signals, making them undetectable by current SETI methods. This challenges the core assumption that artificial signals remain pristine during interstellar travel, forcing a rethink of detection strategies and data re-analysis.","source":{"name":"Future Pulse","url":"https://futurepulse.hr"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/turbulent-plasma-hides-signals/main.jpg","alt":"Turbulent Plasma Hides Signals"},"subtitle":"Zašto bi turbulentna okolina oko egzoplaneta onemogućila detekciju uskih radio-poruka?","subtitleEn":"Why stellar space weather matters for technosignature detection","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/turbulent-plasma-hides-signals/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why stellar space weather matters for technosignature detection"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","space"],"geo":{"name":"Mountain View, United States","lat":37.3861,"lon":-122.0839,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$5b","part1En":"$5c","part2En":"$5d"}]}]]}],["$L5e"],"$L5f"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
